<div id="review_570840462" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/570840462" />
    <a title="Catie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1886642-catie"><img alt="Catie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1385169623p2/1886642.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/570840462?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Catie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Catie" href="/user/show/1886642-catie">Catie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781600247378" href="/book/show/6702378-brief-interviews-with-hideous-men">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=read-in-2013">read-in-2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer570840462" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11973663336530807452">There were moments of absolute brilliance (<i>Forever Overhead</i> was my favorite). There were also moments when I would have done anything to get him to stop talking. And he does this completely ingenious thing where, by omitting the interview questions, he essentially turns you (the reader) into the interviewer. The questions are so obvious in relation to the answers that I found myself mentally supplying them during the pauses, which made me feel like I was trapped into participating in conversatio</span>
  <span id="freeText11973663336530807452" style="display:none">There were moments of absolute brilliance (<i>Forever Overhead</i> was my favorite). There were also moments when I would have done anything to get him to stop talking. And he does this completely ingenious thing where, by omitting the interview questions, he essentially turns you (the reader) into the interviewer. The questions are so obvious in relation to the answers that I found myself mentally supplying them during the pauses, which made me feel like I was trapped into participating in conversations with these “hideous” men – not always a comfortable experience. On the other hand, I’ve never been one of those readers who wants to feel comfortable all the time. And I have to admit that a large part of my discomfort stemmed from the amount that I ended up sympathizing with some of these men. Whether through momentary glimpses of vulnerability or through sheer wordy use of what I can only refer to as “crazypants logic,” his characters did pull some small amount of sympathy from me - as much as it pained me to give it.<br /><br />It will also be of interest to some (Infinite Readalong buddies!) that the author narrates the audiobook himself. He is an excellent narrator; although, he did make me wonder if I’ve been mispronouncing “coital” for my entire life.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11973663336530807452" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


